    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      Lota Creek and the foreshore areas provide outdoor amenity that gives the suburb a distinctive identity within the bayside corridor. For families with young children and for retirees seeking a lifestyle-oriented base, the proximity to the water is not an incidental feature: it is the reason they chose this part of Brisbane. Manly Boat Harbour and the Cambridge Parade dining and retail precinct in neighbouring Manly are within easy reach, meaning Lota residents enjoy the amenity of a more prominent bayside suburb without paying the Manly premium. For the committed bayside buyer who has been comparing addresses along the corridor, Lota represents the point where the lifestyle becomes accessible.
    </p>
    <p style="font-family:var(--font-sans); font-size:1rem; font-weight:300; line-height:1.8; color:#4a4540; margin-bottom:1.25rem;">
      The housing stock in Lota includes a mix of established family homes, post-war brick houses, and renovated properties that reflect the suburb's appeal to buyers who recognise the location and the lifestyle but want the practical benefits of a modernised home. Blocks tend to be generous by bayside standards. Sellers who understand how the Lota buyer thinks, and who present their property to speak directly to that buyer's lifestyle priorities, consistently achieve the best results when a campaign goes to market.
    </p>
